# Backend Conventions

The backend (`src/`) is a set of FastAPI services following a hexagonal
(ports & adapters) architecture mirrored from the **paymentgate** repo. Keep new
code consistent with the patterns below.

## Layering & dependency rule

- **domain/** — pure business logic. NO framework imports (no FastAPI,
  SQLAlchemy, httpx). Holds: `entities`, `commands`, `queries`, `exceptions`, `ports/`.
- **adapters/** — concrete implementations of domain ports: `http/` (FastAPI),
  `database/` (repositories + unit of work), `predictor/` (ml only).
- **common/** — shared building blocks reused by every service: `application/`,
  `core/`, `http/`, `core/entities/`, `adapters/bus/`.
- Allowed flow: `adapters -> domain` (only through ports). `domain` NEVER imports
  adapters or frameworks. Cross-cutting concerns live in `common`.

## Business logic: Commands & Queries

- **Writes** subclass `common.core.commands.Command`:
  - a frozen nested `Context` dataclass holds validated input;
  - put input validation in `Context.validate_context()`, raising `ContextValidationError`;
  - implement a single `async execute() -> CommandResult[T]`;
  - open the transaction with `async with self.uow:`.
- **Reads** are plain async functions in `domain/queries.py` that take the `uow`;
  raise `NotFound` when an entity is missing.
- HTTP handlers stay thin: build the `Context` from the Pydantic payload, run the
  command/query, wrap the result in a response envelope. No business logic in handlers.

## Ports & adapters

- Declare abstractions in `domain/ports/` with `abc.ABC` + `@abc.abstractmethod`
  (repositories, uow, predictor).
- Implement them under `adapters/`. Persistence sits behind a `UnitOfWork`
  (`common.core.ports.uow.UnitOfWork`) that commits on clean exit / rolls back on
  exception via `__aexit__`.
- Wire concrete adapters in `lifespan.py` onto `app.state` (e.g.
  `app.state.uow_factory`) and expose them to handlers via
  `adapters/http/dependencies.py` + FastAPI `Depends`.
- Swapping an implementation (in-memory → SQLAlchemy/asyncpg) must not touch domain.

## Messaging (Kafka)

Follow the **paymentgate** event-bus pattern:

- **Streams (Kafka topics):** `EventStream` `StrEnum` in `common/core/entities/events.py`.
  Enum member names are domain-oriented; values are the topic strings used in Kafka
  and `docs/ARCHITECTURE.md`. Bootstrap topics from `EventStream.all_streams()`.
- **Event types:** `EventKind` `StrEnum` in the same module (PascalCase values).
- **Payload:** `Event` dataclass (`kind`, `source`, `aggregate_id`, `stream`, `payload`,
  `meta`, …) with `as_dict()` for serialization. Do not invent parallel envelope types.
- **Port:** `EventBus` in `common/core/ports/bus.py` — `send_to_bus`, `get_messages`,
  `commit`, `move_ptr_to_commited`. Domain code never imports `aiokafka`.
- **Adapters:** `KafkaEventBus` and helpers (`get_producer`, `get_consumer`) in
  `common/adapters/bus/kafka.py`; `InMemEventBus` in `common/adapters/bus/in_mem.py`.
- **Wiring:** in `lifespan.py`, create producer/consumer (or `InMemEventBus.instance()`),
  pass `KafkaEventBus(producer=…)` / `KafkaEventBus(consumer=…)` into handlers.
  Use `run_consumer_loop` for Kafka polling; subscribe handlers on `InMemEventBus`
  when `KAFKA_ENABLED=false`.
- Service-specific handlers live in `<service>/adapters/messaging/` and delegate to
  domain `queries`/`commands` — filter by `EventKind`, publish with `send_to_bus`.
- Install the `messaging` poetry group in Dockerfiles for services that use the bus.
- Reset `InMemEventBus` in `conftest.py` via `InMemEventBus.reset()`.

## ML (XGBoost)

All outcome-prediction and future ranking models that use gradient boosting must follow
the official **[XGBoost stable documentation](https://xgboost.readthedocs.io/en/stable/)**.
Treat it as the source of truth for install, API usage, objectives, and deployment —
do not rely on blog posts or outdated snippets.

- **Dependency:** declare `xgboost` (and related libs: `numpy`, `scikit-learn`, `shap`) in
  the Poetry **`ml`** group in `pyproject.toml`. Pin versions there; bump only after checking
  the [release notes](https://xgboost.readthedocs.io/en/stable/changes/index.html).
- **Local install:** `make install_ml` or `poetry install --with ml`. See the
  [Installation Guide](https://xgboost.readthedocs.io/en/stable/install.html) for platform
  wheels (Linux/macOS/Windows). **macOS:** install OpenMP first (`brew install libomp`) before
  importing XGBoost.
- **Layering:** domain depends on `OutcomePredictor` (`ml/domain/ports/predictor.py`) only.
  XGBoost imports belong in `ml/adapters/predictor/` (e.g. a trained model loader), never in
  `domain/` or HTTP handlers. SHAP explainability stays in the adapter layer alongside the model.
- **Scaffold vs production:** the repo ships `BaselineOutcomePredictor` so `make test` runs
  without the `ml` group. When wiring a real model, implement `OutcomePredictor` using patterns
  from [Get Started](https://xgboost.readthedocs.io/en/stable/get_started.html) and
  [Python API](https://xgboost.readthedocs.io/en/stable/python/python_api.html); load via
  `lifespan.py` onto `app.state.predictor`.
- **Objectives & tutorials:** choose objectives and training flows from the official tutorials
  (e.g. [Learning to Rank](https://xgboost.readthedocs.io/en/stable/tutorials/learning_to_rank.html)
  for Search reranking, standard classification/regression for outcome prediction). Document the
  chosen objective and feature schema in the adapter module docstring.
- **Docker / deploy:** when the ML service uses XGBoost in production, install the group in
  `src/ml/Dockerfile` (`poetry install --only main,ml,messaging --no-root` or equivalent).
  Linux containers use PyPI manylinux wheels per the install guide; GPU (`device=cuda`) is
  optional and follows [GPU Support](https://xgboost.readthedocs.io/en/stable/gpu/index.html).
- **Tests:** keep domain tests on `BaselineOutcomePredictor` or fakes; add adapter-level tests
  for XGBoost serialization/load/predict paths. Default CI may omit the `ml` group unless
  integration tests require it.

## Exceptions

Follow the **paymentgate** layered exception model (`paymentgate/src/common/core/exceptions.py`).
NeuroAtlas uses the same rules; names map as follows:

| Layer | paymentgate | NeuroAtlas (today) | Raise in |
|-------|-------------|-------------------|----------|
| Domain / service | `ServiceException` | `DomainError` subclasses (`NotFound`, `ContextValidationError`, `InvalidOperation`) | `domain/commands.py`, `domain/queries.py`, domain tasks |
| Adapter / infra | `AdapterException` | `BusException` (+ future `DatabaseException`) | `adapters/database/`, `adapters/bus/`, external gateways |
| HTTP / API | `APIException`, `HTTPException` | FastAPI handlers + `register_exception_handlers` for `DomainError` | `adapters/http/` only |

**Dependency rule (same as paymentgate):**

- Domain code raises **`DomainError`** only — never `BusException`, never bare `Exception`.
- Adapters wrap infrastructure failures in **`BusException`** / **`DatabaseException`** (when DB lands).
- HTTP handlers stay thin: build command/query context, execute, return envelope. Let
  `register_exception_handlers` map `DomainError` → HTTP status; do not catch domain errors
  in handlers unless translating to a different response shape.
- A lower-layer exception may propagate upward (adapter → domain → HTTP), but never raise an
  HTTP/API exception from domain or adapters.

**Orchestration pattern (tasks, Kafka handlers, background loops):**

Re-raise adapter/infrastructure errors; log and contain everything else so one bad message
does not kill the worker. Mirror paymentgate `tasks.py` / `domain/tasks.py`:

```python
try:
    await command.execute()
except DatabaseException:
    raise
except BusException:
    raise
except Exception as exc:
    await logger.aerror("Failure while processing batch.", exc_info=exc)
```

For **Kafka consumers**, after logging a non-infrastructure failure, commit/skip the event
so the partition does not stall (see paymentgate `consume_inbox_events`). Infrastructure
errors (`BusException`, `DatabaseException`) are logged and **re-raised** so the caller can
retry or fail fast.

**Logging:**

- Use `await logger.aerror(..., exc_info=exc)` or `await logger.aexception(...)` — never `print`.
- Include correlation fields (`event_id`, `aggregate_id`, `kind`, `stream`) on bus/task paths.

**Adding new exceptions:**

- Subclass the correct layer in `common/core/exceptions.py` (domain) or the service’s
  `domain/exceptions.py` if service-specific.
- Give `DomainError` subclasses a `status_code` when they surface over HTTP.
- Do not introduce parallel error types in adapters when a domain or adapter base class fits.

## App wiring, errors & responses

- Build every service app through `common.application.app_factory.create(...)`
  (shared CORS, error envelope, `/health`). Don't hand-roll `FastAPI()` per service.
- Service settings subclass `common.application.settings.Settings`; read env vars there.
  Local and Docker runs load values from `infra/.env` (Makefile `-include` + compose
  `--env-file infra/.env`). Edit `.env`, not `.env.example`.
- Raise `DomainError` subclasses from domain — see **Exceptions** above. `register_exception_handlers`
  maps them to the uniform `ErrorSchema`.
- Wrap successful output in `ResponseSchema` / `ListResponseSchema` /
  `PaginatedResponseSchema` (`common.http.schemas`).
- IDs are ULID-based with a type prefix (e.g. `pat_`, `asm_`).

## Logging & metrics (observability)

- Use the shared structlog logger `common.application.logging.logger` with the
  async API and bound kwargs: `await logger.ainfo("event", patient_id=pid)`.
  JSON output, never `print`.
- Metrics use `prometheus-client` (already a dependency). When wiring it, mount a
  `/metrics` ASGI app and keep module-level Counters/Histograms in the app/adapter
  layer — never instrument the domain. *(Declared but not yet wired — follow this
  when adding it.)*

## Tests

- pytest with `asyncio_mode=auto`; write `async def test_*` functions in files
  `test_*.py` under `src/<service>/tests/`, mirroring the module path
  (e.g. `tests/test_domain/`).
- Test domain logic against in-memory adapters; reset shared state with an autouse
  fixture in `conftest.py` (`reset_store`).
- Run `make test` or `make test_<service>` (with coverage). Coverage omits
  `__init__`, `settings`, `domain/ports`, and tests.

## Quality gates / CI-CD

- Before pushing, `make check` must pass = `fmt` (isort --profile black + ruff
  format) + `lint` (ruff + mypy) + `test`. Run `make sast` (bandit) for security.
- Lint/format config lives in `pyproject.toml`: ruff line-length 120, target
  py312, mccabe max-complexity 10.
- Each service ships a `src/<service>/Dockerfile` (non-root user,
  `poetry install --only main,<group>`); compose files under `infra/` run local
  infra (`infra.compose.yml`) and app services (`application.compose.yml`).
- CI must run these same gates (`fmt_check`, `lint`, `test`, `sast`, docker build)
  on every PR. *(No pipeline file exists yet — when adding CI, drive it from the
  Makefile targets so local and CI stay identical.)*
